bootrom — auditable reverse-engineering of HiSilicon/Goke mask-ROMs
====================================================================

This tree reconstructs the on-chip mask-ROM (bootrom) of each supported SoC
into reviewable C and ARM assembly. The mask-ROM is the root of trust for
every later boot stage that openhisilicon already replaces in kernel/ and
libraries/; auditing it pins down which authentication, KLAD, RSA, SPACC,
TRNG, and update-mode behaviour the SoC ships with by silicon.

Per-chip layout (mirrored across siblings as each one is brought online):

  bootrom/<chip>/
    MANIFEST                  tracked: chip id, dump size, sha256, first16
                              bytes, ipctool version
    Makefile                  disasm | build | verify | clean
    re/                       clean-room reverse-engineered source
      <chip>-regmap.h         umbrella header
      regmap-*.h              per-block register offsets, only what's used
      start.S                 reset vectors, _start, clear-remap trampoline
      bootloader.c            C bodies (utilities first, main flow later)
    scratchpad/               human-readable analysis notes
      bootrom.txt             hex + mnemonic + commentary (vector page)
      functions.txt           func ledger: address, name, signature
      sram.txt                SRAM layout discovered during analysis

The raw .bin and the disassembler output stay local — see .gitignore. Each
contributor reproduces them with scripts/dump.sh and scripts/disasm.sh.

Methodological inspiration: TekuConcept's unfinished hi3516cv500 RE at
https://github.com/TekuConcept/HI3516CV500-SDK (sdk/bootrom/). No files
from that project are imported; av300 is reverse-engineered fresh from
its own dump.

Workflow
--------

  # 1. Dump the mask-ROM from a live camera (requires ipctool with the
  #    bootrom subcommand — present in master since May 2026).
  bootrom/scripts/dump.sh openipc-hi3516av300.dlab.doty.ru hi3516av300

  # 2. Verify the local dump matches the tracked MANIFEST.
  bootrom/scripts/verify.sh hi3516av300

  # 3. Produce an annotated disassembly (local-only).
  bootrom/scripts/disasm.sh hi3516av300

  # 4. Sanity-build the RE'd source — must compile cleanly under
  #    arm-none-eabi-gcc with -nostdlib -ffreestanding.
  make -C bootrom/hi3516av300 build

The build target produces re.elf, which is NOT flashable — it is a
parser/well-formedness gate, not a bit-identical reconstruction. Matching
the original mask-ROM byte-for-byte would require knowing the exact
compiler, version, and flags HiSilicon used, which is out of scope.


Findings from the hi3516av300 reversal
=======================================

This section captures observations worth knowing before auditing or
extending the av300 reverse-engineered source. Each item references
addresses in the original mask-ROM (re/bootloader.c is the C side).


Structural findings
-------------------

* **Boot dispatch.** main() at 0x4002704 picks one of four boot paths
  based on two SYSCTRL state bits sampled once on entry:
    PERISTAT bit 0 set  → bootrom_secure_check  (signed/RSA path)
    SYSSTAT  bit 5 set  → fastboot_update       (UART recovery)
    SYSSTAT  bit 4 set  → bootrom_alt_media     (eMMC raw)
    else                → config_use_flash      (NOR/parallel flash)
  is_update_mode() interposes between fastboot and flash/alt — if the
  recovery button (GPIO0 pin 0) is held low for ~20 seconds, media_update
  is tried directly before any of the above. PERISTAT bits 4..5 then
  further select between fastboot-media and alt-media inside
  media_update.

* **Image header magic.** parse_image_header (0x40001dc) validates a
  "MBSB" magic (0x4253424d) at the start of the loaded image, plus a
  per-mode descriptor table at offset 0x510..0x520. The validation here
  is structural — field-range checks only — not cryptographic. RSA
  signature verification happens later inside klad_dispatch_sig (still
  a stub at the time of writing).

* **Four-word cross-check.** config_use_flash and bootrom_alt_media
  both do `r3==r2 && r0==r3 && r2==r1` over the first 16 bytes of the
  loaded image as an early sanity check. This is again structural, not
  cryptographic — a sentinel pattern check, not a hash.

* **Status magics.** Several little-endian ASCII constants pass state
  through SYSCTRL slots and SRAM:
    "ziju"  (0x7a696a75)  SYSCTRL[0x140]  bootloader-ack from media path
    "DOWN"  (0x444f574e)  SYSCTRL[0x13c]  download mode is active
    "EMMC"  (0x454d4d43)  SYSCTRL[0x150]  loaded payload returned cleanly
    "MBSB"  (0x4253424d)  image[0]        valid image header
  uart0_recv_payload spins on SYSCTRL[0x150] looking for "EMMC" after
  the loaded payload runs — that is how the payload signals back into
  the bootrom.

* **DDR PHY randomization.** refresh_ddr (0x4000358) consumes four TRNG
  random values to randomize DDR PHY tap calibration — an intentional
  anti-bias measure. The boot timing therefore has nontrivial entropy
  on every cold start. If TRNG returns deterministic values (failure
  or attack), PHY calibration falls back to a deterministic path.

* **clear_remap thunk.** The first six instructions at SDRAM_START
  decide where execution resumes after the bootrom clears the SC_CTRL
  remap bit. The thunk itself is memcpy32'd from bootrom 0x9c to
  SDRAM 0x4016500 before being executed. This is the moment of
  handover — the bootrom is no longer in control after `mov pc, r0`
  at 0x40000b4.

* **Recovery-console pinmux.** When SYSSTAT bit 4 is clear (default
  boot), main() programs IOCFG1[0..5] with vendor-specific values
  (0x6c1 / 0x4f1×4 / 0x5f1) — almost certainly UART0 plus a couple of
  GPIO function selects for the recovery console. uart0_send_status's
  output "\nE<code>D<extra>" is the boot-failure signature visible
  on this console.

* **Compiler tells.** configure_soc_clocks (0x4000140), reset_soc_clocks
  (0x40001b0), and the timer_{start,stop,reset_counter} family all
  compile back to byte-identical instruction sequences. That is a
  strong signal the original was written in straightforward C with
  similar idioms — useful when proposing changes (the compiler is
  unlikely to surprise you on these). main() and the larger media /
  klad paths compile with the same CFG but reordered basic blocks.


Boot-attack surface
-------------------

These observations are not theoretical vulnerabilities — they are
properties of the bootrom that an attacker with the listed precondition
could potentially exploit. Each assumes the chip is in non-secure boot
mode (PERISTAT bit 0 clear); a secure-mode chip routes everything
through the still-stubbed KLAD/RSA chain and would refuse anything
that does not pass klad_dispatch_sig at 0x4000868.

* **Physical SD-card swap (most realistic).** Sequence:
    1. Pull SD/eMMC, mount on workbench.
    2. Write a crafted MBR at block 0 with the standard 0x55/0xaa
       signature plus partition entries pointing at attacker-staged
       sectors.
    3. Stage a payload with valid "MBSB" header (magic + matching
       mode/mode2 fields + 16-byte all-equal-words sentinel at the
       start).
    4. Reinsert media, power up.
  Result: media_program_b (0x4004d8c) accepts the MBR signature,
  walks the partition table without strict bounds-checking, then
  hands the partition contents to media_finalize_b which copies
  them into DDR at 0x81000000 and invokes_foreign_code() into them.
  Defence: keep PERISTAT bit 0 set in OTP so the secure path runs
  klad_dispatch_sig.

* **Physical UART access (also realistic).** Sequence:
    1. Attach to the recovery UART pads (TX/RX/GND on PCB).
    2. Within ~20 seconds of power-on, reply 0xAA to the bootrom's
       "are you there?" 0x20-probe at uart0_wait_start_frame.
    3. Drive the framing protocol: ENTER → DATA × N → END,
       each acked with 0xAA/0x55/0xAA respectively.
    4. burn_bootloader (0x40034ac) accepts the framed payload and
       invokes it via uart0_recv_payload's callback dispatch.
  Result: same as the SD path — arbitrary code execution as the
  bootrom, with full DDR + KLAD register access. Defence: same as
  above; secure mode forces RSA verify of the received image.

* **Recovery-button race.** Sequence:
    1. Hold GPIO0 pin 0 low across power-on for 20+ seconds.
    2. is_update_mode (0x400105c) returns 1 after three consecutive
       LOW samples.
    3. main()'s update-mode branch runs media_update directly
       without entering the secure dispatch.
  Result: forces the alt-media path even if the chip was configured
  for flash boot. Useful for recovery; useful for attack iff combined
  with a media swap.

* **SRAM[0x188] clock-state flag.** After invoke_foreign_code,
  invoke_foreign_code sets SRAM[0x188] = 1. main()'s success path
  reads this slot and SKIPS reset_soc_clocks if it is non-zero.
  Result: an attacker-controlled payload that wants to leave the
  clock tree in a high-frequency state for a follow-up second-stage
  attack just needs to set this single SRAM word.

* **Four-word check is bypassable.** The early sentinel check is a
  byte-for-byte equality of the first four 32-bit words. Trivially
  satisfied by 16 zero bytes (or any 16 bytes of the same word
  repeated). It exists to detect erased media — it is not a
  signature and should not be relied on for trust.

* **"EMMC" magic race in SYSCTRL[0x150].** uart0_recv_payload spins
  on this slot to detect the loaded payload returning. The slot is
  writable from any code that has SYSCTRL mapped. A foreign payload
  that did not actually finish but writes the magic anyway would
  trick the bootrom into returning cleanly — followed by
  disable_instruction_cache, optional reset_soc_clocks, timer_stop,
  and the clear_remap handover. Combined with the SRAM[0x188] flag,
  this gives precise control over the bootrom-to-payload handover
  state.

* **Glitch window at clear_remap.** Between memcpy32 copying the
  thunk to SDRAM at 0x4016500 and the `LDR PC, =0x4016500` jump,
  the bootrom is still running but SDRAM is writable from any DMA-
  capable peripheral (USB, eMMC, SDIO0). A targeted EM injection
  or voltage glitch during this window — roughly 6 instructions —
  could alter the thunk before it runs. The thunk's only job is to
  clear SC_CTRL bit 8 and jump to *(SDRAM_START), so altering the
  jump target would let an attacker run arbitrary code with the
  remap-already-cleared state set up.

RSA verification chain — what we now know
------------------------------------------

The 9 KLAD primitives plus klad_setup have been structurally
reversed. Concrete findings worth flagging for crypto auditors:

* **OTP[0x50..0x6c] is a SHA-256 digest of the trusted public key,
  not the key itself.** Reversing klad_rsa_chain confirms the full
  trust chain:
    1. OTP at 0x100a0050..0x6c = 32-byte fingerprint H(pubkey)
    2. The image header CARRIES the public-key modulus at
       SDRAM+0x510 (the descriptor table base, populated by
       parse_image_header from the on-media image)
    3. klad_validate_header SHA-hashes the image-supplied modulus
       and compares the digest to OTP via strncmp
    4. klad_dispatch_sig then RSA-verifies the image signature
       using the validated modulus
  So the trust anchor in OTP is JUST 32 bytes; everything else is
  attacker-influenceable until the SHA digest matches. To forge:
  attacker would need a SHA-256 preimage attack on the OTP value
  (≈2^256 work — infeasible) OR a separate RSA private key whose
  public modulus hashes to the same OTP value (also 2^256).
  Practical exploitation requires OEM-key compromise — i.e. the
  factorization of a 1024-bit RSA key.

* **klad_setup is the SHA padding wrapper, NOT key loading.** This
  was the single most important reversal of the session: klad_setup
  (0x400072c) appends standard SHA-2 padding (0x80 + zeros + big-
  endian 64-bit bit-length) to the source buffer **in place**, runs
  the SPACC SHA engine, then **restores the original bytes** from a
  120-byte snapshot taken before padding. The "key loading" lives
  inside the RSA0 hardware (modulus presumably baked into the chip
  at silicon manufacture, or loaded from OTP at a slot still TBD).
  klad_setup's three SHA leaves (sha_init at 0x40006e0, sha_compute
  at 0x4000654, sha_write_output at 0x4003bcc) remain as stubs —
  reversing them traces the SPACC accelerator register sequence.

* **RSA0 hardware sequence is fully reversed.** klad_dispatch_sig
  (0x4000868, 509 instructions, now fully inlined in
  bootloader.c) drives RSA0 directly:
    RSA0[0x54] = ((mode>>7) - 1) << 2            mode-length register
    RSA0[0x58] = modulus[i]    for i in 0..mode/4    stream pubkey
    RSA0[0x5c] = signature[i]  for i in 0..mode/4    stream signature
    RSA0[0x68] = 5                                kick exponentiation
    rsa0_kick(RSA0+0x50, 200ms timeout)           wait completion
    hash_buf[i] = RSA0[0x64]   for i in 0..mode/4    read recovered M
    RSA0[0x54] |= 0x72; RSA0[0x68] = 5; kick      second op
    PKCS#1 v1.5 padding parse using lookup table  bootrom 0x7e28
    strncmp embedded digest vs SHA(message)       final compare
  The "klad_rsa_chain" placeholder was an artefact of the
  earlier structural reversal — there is no separate function
  at 0x4000aac, it's a branch target inside klad_dispatch_sig.

* **Mode dispatch is on RSA key SIZE in bytes (not bits).** klad_
  dispatch_sig's mode field (ctx[2] = image_header[8..b]) maps:
      mode == 0x200   → 4096-bit RSA (special path at 0x4000b9c)
      mode == 0x100   → 2048-bit RSA via klad_rsa_chain loop
      mode == 0x80    → 1024-bit RSA via klad_rsa_chain loop
      mode <= 0x7f    → ERROR path (uart status "61", return -1)
  parse_image_header (0x40001dc) only accepts mode ∈ {0x80, 0x100,
  0x200} so an attacker cannot directly downgrade below 1024 bits.
  But mode = 0x80 is 1024-bit RSA, which is below modern security
  margins — an SoC running secure boot accepts a 1024-bit signed
  image identically to a 4096-bit signed one. If an attacker
  controls one weak 1024-bit RSA key signed by the chip OEM, they
  can sign arbitrary images.

* **SHA chain via SPACC.** klad_finalize (0x400136c) runs a
  6-step SHA pipeline (init → load_const → update → chunk × 2
  → close → check) against a 64-byte working buffer. The
  SPACC accelerator drives this; klad_finalize_check (0x4000614)
  compares the digest against a value passed in. The digest size
  and which fields feed the chunks is still inside the stubbed
  SHA helpers.

* **strncmp side-channel in klad_validate_header.** The OTP-vs-
  header signature comparison uses strncmp, which short-circuits
  on first mismatch. The bootrom is not running under any timing-
  attack mitigation, so on a chip with measurable boot-time
  delta (e.g. UART debug enabled), an attacker can in principle
  learn the OTP signature byte-by-byte over many boots. Real-world
  exploitability depends on whether boot timing is visible and
  whether the boot rejects-then-retries with the same image — the
  bootrom does reset on failure, so the attacker gets one
  measurement per boot cycle.

* **SHA padding in-place mutation.** klad_setup writes 64+8 bytes
  of SHA padding past the message tail before hashing, then
  restores. If the bootrom is preempted between the destructive
  write and the restore (e.g. by EM injection, voltage glitch),
  the loaded image is left with corrupted bytes at offset
  size..size+72. Whether this becomes exploitable depends on what
  the post-hash flow does with those bytes — they fall inside
  the signature region for klad_dispatch_sig's iteration, which
  could lead to a mid-verify glitch.

The remaining inner stubs are 9 RSA0/SPACC/SHA hardware-driver
primitives (rsa0_kick, the 6 klad_sha_* helpers, sha_init/compute/
output, klad_finalize_check, klad_check_step, klad_alt_step) plus
2 alt-media transit functions. The major remaining unknown is the
exact PKCS#1 padding table at bootrom 0x7e28 — 256 bytes of
lookup-table data that classify each byte as "valid pad" or "data".
Dumping and decoding that table would tell us whether the bootrom
accepts standard PKCS#1 v1.5 padding or a vendor-modified variant.


Reading order suggestion for new auditors
-----------------------------------------

  1. scratchpad/bootrom.txt — annotated hex of the vector page and
     reset trampoline (first ~512 bytes).
  2. re/start.S — _entry, _start, clear_remap thunk, _dead_loop,
     memcpy32, the four cache/control-feature MCR ops.
  3. re/bootloader.c, top half — leaf utilities (memset/memcpy/strXxx,
     timer, UART, eMMC, configure/reset_soc_clocks).
  4. re/bootloader.c, main() at 0x4002704 — the four-path dispatch.
  5. re/bootloader.c, the four giants — initialize_emmc,
     klad_load_keys, klad_verify, klad_alt_verify.
  6. scratchpad/functions.txt — full ledger; cross-check anything
     surprising against disasm.txt locally.
  7. re/stubs.c — the still-stubbed frontier; this is where the
     audit work continues.
